building blocks of the universe

00:21:05.790 --> 00:21:12.030 align:middle line:10%
are the acts of us looking
and observing the universe."

00:21:12.030 --> 00:21:14.340 align:middle line:10%
Wheeler said, and
this is a quote,

00:21:14.340 --> 00:21:18.610 align:middle line:10%
"we are part of a universe
that is a work in progress.

00:21:18.610 --> 00:21:21.990 align:middle line:10%
We are tiny patches of the
universe looking at itself

00:21:21.990 --> 00:21:23.790 align:middle line:10%
and building itself."

00:21:23.790 --> 00:21:28.170 align:middle line:10%
We live in what he called
"a participatory universe."

00:21:28.170 --> 00:21:29.640 align:middle line:90%
I love this.

00:21:29.640 --> 00:21:33.180 align:middle line:84%
We live in a
participatory universe.

00:21:33.180 --> 00:21:35.580 align:middle line:84%
Think about what John
Wheeler has just said.

00:21:35.580 --> 00:21:41.250 align:middle line:84%
He said that the universe exists
because we are creating it

00:21:41.250 --> 00:21:42.480 align:middle line:90%
as we go along.

00:21:42.480 --> 00:21:45.600 align:middle line:84%
It's a very, very different idea
from conventional physics that

00:21:45.600 --> 00:21:47.970 align:middle line:84%
says the universe
was here first,

00:21:47.970 --> 00:21:51.330 align:middle line:84%
and we've come along
later as an afterthought,

00:21:51.330 --> 00:21:53.370 align:middle line:84%
and that we have
very little influence

00:21:53.370 --> 00:21:54.690 align:middle line:90%
in the world around us.

00:21:54.690 --> 00:21:57.990 align:middle line:84%
Wheeler is saying
that we are actually

00:21:57.990 --> 00:21:59.010 align:middle line:90%
building this universe.

00:21:59.010 --> 00:21:59.940 align:middle line:90%
It's not finished yet.

00:21:59.940 --> 00:22:04.230 align:middle line:84%
We are still building in
a participatory universe.

00:22:04.230 --> 00:22:07.650 align:middle line:84%
And I want to take just
a moment, just a moment,

00:22:07.650 --> 00:22:10.920 align:middle line:84%
and really dive in to
the implications of what

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:12.810 align:middle line:90%
Wheeler has just said here.

00:22:12.810 --> 00:22:15.240 align:middle line:84%
What he's saying is
that we will probably

00:22:15.240 --> 00:22:17.940 align:middle line:84%
never find the smallest
particle in the universe.

00:22:17.940 --> 00:22:20.640 align:middle line:84%
The particle that they're
looking for at CERN,

00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:22.680 align:middle line:84%
he said, we'll probably
never find that.

00:22:22.680 --> 00:22:24.990 align:middle line:84%
He also is implying
that we will probably

00:22:24.990 --> 00:22:29.610 align:middle line:84%
never find the edge of the
universe and what's beyond.

00:22:29.610 --> 00:22:31.530 align:middle line:84%
We're building
machines, telescopes

00:22:31.530 --> 00:22:33.780 align:middle line:84%
that keep looking
further, and further,

00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:36.150 align:middle line:84%
and further to the
edge of the universe.

00:22:36.150 --> 00:22:37.830 align:middle line:84%
Wheeler is saying,
we'll never find it.

00:22:37.830 --> 00:22:38.790 align:middle line:90%
And here's why.

00:22:38.790 --> 00:22:40.420 align:middle line:90%
Here's what he's saying.

00:22:40.420 --> 00:22:42.240 align:middle line:90%
He's saying, the act--

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:47.190 align:middle line:84%
it is the act of you
and I looking, peering

00:22:47.190 --> 00:22:50.430 align:middle line:84%
into the universe
with the expectation

00:22:50.430 --> 00:22:53.670 align:middle line:84%
that something exists
for us to see that is

00:22:53.670 --> 00:22:57.100 align:middle line:90%
an act of creation unto itself.

00:22:57.100 --> 00:23:01.020 align:middle line:84%
So the act of peering into
the smallest, smallest

00:23:01.020 --> 00:23:03.840 align:middle line:84%
particles of matter
with the expectation

00:23:03.840 --> 00:23:05.640 align:middle line:84%
that something is
there is always

00:23:05.640 --> 00:23:07.890 align:middle line:84%
going to put another
particle there for us to see.

00:23:07.890 --> 00:23:09.540 align:middle line:90%
That's exactly what's happening.

00:23:09.540 --> 00:23:12.010 align:middle line:84%
We build bigger
and bigger machines

00:23:12.010 --> 00:23:13.930 align:middle line:84%
with more and more
energy to collide

00:23:13.930 --> 00:23:16.550 align:middle line:84%
these quantum particles that
are breaking into a bazillion

00:23:16.550 --> 00:23:17.350 align:middle line:90%
pieces.

00:23:17.350 --> 00:23:19.780 align:middle line:84%
And every time,
scientists say, aha,

00:23:19.780 --> 00:23:21.640 align:middle line:84%
we've got the ultimate
smallest particle.

00:23:21.640 --> 00:23:25.030 align:middle line:84%
They look a little closer, and
there's something else there.

00:23:25.030 --> 00:23:27.670 align:middle line:10%
It wasn't long ago
scientist using

00:23:27.670 --> 00:23:30.040 align:middle line:10%
radio telescopes
believed they had

00:23:30.040 --> 00:23:31.690 align:middle line:10%
found the edge of the universe.

00:23:31.690 --> 00:23:34.720 align:middle line:10%
They said, we've
reached a boundary,

00:23:34.720 --> 00:23:36.220 align:middle line:10%
the edge of our
universe, that we've

00:23:36.220 --> 00:23:38.200 align:middle line:10%
got to build another
telescope to see

00:23:38.200 --> 00:23:39.850 align:middle line:10%
what's beyond the boundary.

00:23:39.850 --> 00:23:42.450 align:middle line:84%
And they built another,
more powerful telescope.

00:23:42.450 --> 00:23:44.200 align:middle line:84%
And now, they said,
oops, it wasn't really

00:23:44.200 --> 00:23:47.530 align:middle line:84%
the edge because there
is something beyond that.

00:23:47.530 --> 00:23:50.890 align:middle line:84%
What Wheeler is saying
to us, what he's telling

00:23:50.890 --> 00:23:54.970 align:middle line:84%
us is that our role
in The Divine Matrix

00:23:54.970 --> 00:23:59.930 align:middle line:84%
